## Security Is Not a Snapshot

The authorization package documents the security posture of OpenMRS at a specific point in time. But systems change — configurations drift, new vulnerabilities are discovered, threat actors develop new techniques, staff turn over, and the software itself evolves through updates and patches. The moment the authorization is granted, the system begins to diverge from the state that was assessed.

Continuous monitoring is how the organization maintains an accurate picture of security posture between formal assessments — and how it demonstrates to the Authorizing Official that the risk accepted at authorization time remains within acceptable bounds as the system operates over time.

NIST SP 800-137 defines continuous monitoring as maintaining ongoing awareness of information security, vulnerabilities, and threats to support organizational risk management decisions. Task S-5 asks the organization to develop the continuous monitoring strategy before the authorization is granted — not as an afterthought once the ATO is received, but as a documented commitment to how the security program will be sustained.

I want to note a relationship between today's work and Day 30, which developed the initial monitoring strategy as part of the Prepare step. That Day 30 work established the conceptual framework and a preliminary schedule. Task S-5 formalizes that into the official strategy that becomes part of the authorization package — with specific tools, owners, escalation procedures, and integration with the POA&M process.

