## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While developing the alert fatigue management section today I came across the documented details from the post-incident analysis of the **2021 Kaseya VSA ransomware attack** — which affected managed service providers and their clients through a supply chain compromise.

One detail particularly relevant to today's monitoring strategy work: post-incident analysis found that some organizations affected by the Kaseya attack had security monitoring tools that generated alerts during the attack — but those alerts were buried in a high volume of lower-priority findings and were not actioned in time to prevent the ransomware from deploying.

This is the alert fatigue failure mode in a real incident. The monitoring capability existed. The alerts were generated. The response did not happen because the alert volume had conditioned the operations team to prioritize based on volume rather than severity — and the real attack alerts were lost in the noise.

For OpenMRS, this is why the severity-based escalation thresholds documented in today's monitoring strategy matter operationally, not just procedurally. HIGH and CRITICAL GuardDuty findings generate immediate out-of-band notifications to the ISSO — phone and SMS, not just dashboard entries that might be reviewed at the next scheduled interval. The goal is to ensure that genuinely critical alerts are impossible to miss, even in a monitoring environment with a high baseline of lower-priority findings.

The Kaseya case also reinforces the value of the quarterly access recertification. The Kaseya attack propagated through the VSA agent — a trusted, authenticated software component. Regular verification that authenticated access is still appropriate and that no new trusted components have been introduced without authorization is part of the defense against this class of attack.

